BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:warhol-foundation-exhibition-support-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Andy Warhol Foundation: Exhibition Support (Fall 2026 rou
 nd)
DESCRIPTION:Supports solo\, two-person and thematic group exhibitions of co
 ntemporary visual art. The Foundation explicitly prioritises artists whose
  work is under-recognised and whose practices are experimental or hard to 
 categorise\, which makes it a genuine route for media arts\, digital cultu
 re and art-and-science exhibitions rather than a blue-chip-only fund. Gran
 ts of USD 60\,000 to 100\,000 cover direct exhibition costs including arti
 st fees\, new commissions\, catalogue production and artist-designed publi
 c programming\, but not staff salaries. Applicants may request no more tha
 n 25 percent of total direct costs. The proposal is a roughly three-page c
 uratorial letter plus detailed direct-cost budget\, organisational budget 
 and IRS documentation. Deadlines are 1 March and 1 September annually\, wi
 th notifications 1 July and 1 January. IMPORTANT: this is a postmark or em
 ail-timestamp deadline\, not a portal deadline. Fiscal sponsors are explic
 itly not accepted\; the applicant must hold its own IRS ruling letter. The
  six-month-to-two-year timing rule is strict\, so a September 2026 applica
 tion suits exhibitions programmed from mid-2027 onward.\n\nOrganisation: T
 he Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts\nLocation: Applicant's own v
 enue. US-based 501(c)(3) required\; international organisations must first
  submit a letter of inquiry before any proposal is accepted.\nAward: USD 6
 0\,000 to 100\,000. Direct costs only (artist payments\, catalogue and pub
 lication\, artist-designed public programmes)\; staff salaries excluded. R
 equest must not exceed 25 percent of total direct project costs\, which fu
 nctions as a de facto 75 percent co-financing requirement. No application 
 fee.\nDuration: Exhibition must open between 6 months and 2 years after no
 tification.\n\nMore: https://warholfoundation.org/grants/application-guide
 lines/exhibition-support/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium
 =referral
URL:https://warholfoundation.org/grants/application-guidelines/exhibition-s
 upport/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Applicant's own venue. US-based 501(c)(3) required\; international
  organisations must first submit a letter of inquiry before any proposal i
 s accepted.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:warhol-foundation-multiyear-program-support-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Andy Warhol Foundation: Multi-year Program Support (Fall 
 2026 round)
DESCRIPTION:This is the closest thing in US foundation philanthropy to core
  support for an organisation running an ongoing public programme\, as oppo
 sed to a single exhibition. It funds a two-year slate of exhibitions\, res
 idencies\, public art\, screenings\, performances\, lectures and publicati
 ons\, which means a recurring festival or convening series can be underwri
 tten here. Grants are USD 60\,000 to 100\,000 over two years and may not e
 xceed 25 percent of annual operating budget. The Foundation states a prefe
 rence for organisations supporting artists with experimental\, hard-to-cat
 egorise practices\, putting digital culture\, sound art and art-and-scienc
 e programmers squarely in scope. Applications require a forward programme 
 schedule covering at least the twelve months after the award\, a three-pag
 e narrative focused specifically on how artists benefit (the stated centra
 l evaluation criterion)\, a full one-year organisational budget and 501(c)
 (3) documentation. Deadlines are 1 March and 1 September\, notifications 1
  July and 1 January. Fiscal sponsors are not accepted. Organisations that 
 received a Multi-year grant within the past year are ineligible\, and prop
 osals centred on anniversaries\, relocations or major renovations are expl
 icitly discouraged.\n\nOrganisation: The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Vi
 sual Arts\nLocation: Programming delivered by the applicant organisation. 
 US 501(c)(3) required\; international organisations must submit a letter o
 f inquiry first.\nAward: USD 60\,000 to 100\,000 across two years. Request
  must not exceed 25 percent of the organisation's annual operating budget.
  No formal match\, but the 25 percent cap means the balance must come from
  elsewhere. No application fee.\nDuration: Two years of programming\, begi
 nning after the 1 January 2027 notification.\n\nMore: https://warholfounda
 tion.org/grants/application-guidelines/multi-year-program-support/?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://warholfoundation.org/grants/application-guidelines/multi-year-p
 rogram-support/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Programming delivered by the applicant organisation. US 501(c)(3) 
 required\; international organisations must submit a letter of inquiry fir
 st.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:warhol-foundation-small-scale-project-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Andy Warhol Foundation: Project Grants for Small-Scale Or
 ganizations (Fall 2026 round)
DESCRIPTION:Launched in February 2026 as an expansion of the Foundation's p
 rogramme to reach organisations too small for the Exhibition Support and M
 ulti-year strands\, and it is the single most relevant new US scheme for s
 mall media-arts festivals. It funds visual arts projects with a public com
 ponent\, explicitly naming film festivals\, exhibitions\, installations\, 
 residencies and interdisciplinary collaborations. Grants are USD 20\,000 t
 o 30\,000 toward direct costs. The hard gate is the USD 200\,000 annual op
 erating budget ceiling plus US 501(c)(3) status held directly by the appli
 cant\, not via a fiscal sponsor. The Foundation states it assesses creativ
 e risk-taking and the growth of participating artists rather than communit
 y impact metrics\, which suits experimental sound and digital culture prog
 ramming. Proposals are a maximum of three pages plus a one-year operating 
 budget\, a project budget and IRS documentation. Deadlines are 1 March (pr
 ojects begin 1 July or later) and 1 September (projects begin 1 January or
  later). Youth-focused projects are ineligible. One project per round\, an
 d grantees must wait a year after project completion and final reporting b
 efore reapplying.\n\nOrganisation: The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visu
 al Arts\nLocation: Applicant's own venue or programme\, with a mandatory p
 ublic component. US-based only.\nAward: USD 20\,000 to 30\,000 toward dire
 ct costs such as artist payments and production. No application fee.\nDura
 tion: Project must complete within one year of notification\; September-ro
 und projects may begin 1 January 2027 or later.\n\nMore: https://warholfou
 ndation.org/grants/application-guidelines/project-grants-for-small-scale-o
 rganizations/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://warholfoundation.org/grants/application-guidelines/project-gran
 ts-for-small-scale-organizations/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral
LOCATION:Applicant's own venue or programme\, with a mandatory public compo
 nent. US-based only.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:teiger-foundation-hosting-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260909
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260910
SUMMARY:Deadline: Teiger Foundation: Hosting Grant (September 2026 quarterl
 y deadline)
DESCRIPTION:Funds US organisations to present curator-led contemporary visu
 al art exhibitions and projects that originated elsewhere\, on condition t
 he presenting institution meaningfully adapts the project to its own conte
 xt. Teiger's remit covers group exhibitions\, single-artist surveys\, part
 icipatory and community-engaged projects\, digital exhibitions\, and live 
 and virtual performance\, making it one of very few US funders that will d
 irectly finance media-art and performance programming at organisational le
 vel. Requests are fixed at USD 50\,000 or USD 75\,000 with up to 30 percen
 t for indirect costs\, and there is no minimum organisation budget size\, 
 with smaller organisations explicitly favoured for infrastructure support.
  Hosting deadlines are quarterly: 9 September 2026 and 9 December 2026\, b
 oth 17:00 ET\, each mapped to a defined project-opening window roughly a y
 ear out. IMPORTANT: re-presenting a touring project unchanged is explicitl
 y not competitive\; the curatorial adaptation is the substance of the appl
 ication. US 501(c)(3) status is required and the fund is not open to indiv
 iduals or non-US organisations. Teiger's larger biennial Call for Proposal
 s is not running in 2026 and next opens in autumn 2026 with an early-2027 
 deadline.\n\nOrganisation: Teiger Foundation\nLocation: United States. The
  presenting organisation must be US-based\, though the originating project
  may have come from anywhere in the world.\nAward: USD 50\,000 or USD 75\,
 000 (fixed request tiers\, applicant chooses). Up to 30 percent may cover 
 indirect and overhead costs. Organisations with annual budgets under USD 3
 .5 million receive special consideration for infrastructure costs. No matc
 hing requirement. No application fee.\nDuration: Roughly 12 months\; the 9
  September 2026 deadline covers projects opening between 1 April 2027 and 
 31 March 2028.\n\nMore: https://teigerfoundation.org/what-we-fund-how-to-a
 pply/hosting?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://teigerfoundation.org/what-we-fund-how-to-apply/hosting?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. The presenting organisation must be US-based\, thou
 gh the originating project may have come from anywhere in the world.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wave-hill-van-lier-ankhlave-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260810
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260811
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wave Hill / AnkhLave Arts Alliance: 2027 Van Lier Fellows
 hip (NYC)
DESCRIPTION:Wave Hill\, in partnership with AnkhLave Arts Alliance\, invite
 s NYC-based artists who identify as BIPOC to apply for the 2027 Van Lier F
 ellowship as part of the 9th Annual AnkhLave Garden Project at Wave Hill P
 ublic Garden and Cultural Center in the Bronx. The project supports artist
 s who draw on research\, scholarship and lived knowledge to present site-r
 esponsive work at the intersection of nature\, culture and place\, engagin
 g with Wave Hill's plant collections\, history\, design and architecture. 
 The Van Lier Fellowship (funded by the Edward and Sally Van Lier Fund thro
 ugh the New York Community Trust) will be awarded to two NYC-based visual 
 artists aged 30 or younger. FELLOWSHIP: participation in the Winter Worksp
 ace residency (23 February - 18 April 2027)\; a $10\,435 stipend including
  an $8\,000 honorarium and transportation stipend\; a solo exhibition in t
 he Sunroom or Sun Porch (15 May - 4 July 2027)\; public engagement through
  Winter Workspace programming and a Meet the Artist program\; mentorship w
 ith Wave Hill curatorial staff\, working artists and arts professionals\; 
 and AnkhLave Alumni Network benefits. ELIGIBILITY: emerging artists 30 or 
 younger (born 1997 or after) from historically underrepresented communitie
 s\; live in one of the five NYC boroughs\; demonstrate financial need\; ha
 ve completed college and not be enrolled in a degree-granting program duri
 ng the residency\; not represented by a commercial gallery\; available for
  both programs\; cannot have been a Van Lier Fellow elsewhere or have prev
 iously done a Winter Workspace residency or exhibited at Wave Hill or with
  AnkhLave. Works may not include nudity\, depictions of violence or profan
 ity. Artists may apply to only one of the two 2027 AnkhLave Garden Project
  opportunities. Questions: visualarts@wavehill.org with '2027 Van Lier-Ank
 hlave' in the subject. DEADLINE: 10 August 2026. Apply via SlideRoom.\n\nO
 rganisation: Wave Hill / AnkhLave Arts Alliance\nLocation: Wave Hill Publi
 c Garden and Cultural Center\, the Bronx\, New York City\, USA. For NYC-ba
 sed BIPOC visual artists aged 30 or younger.\nAward: $10\,435 stipend\, in
 cluding an $8\,000 honorarium\, a transportation stipend for the residency
 \, and professional development opportunities\, plus the Winter Workspace 
 residency\, a solo exhibition with public programs\, mentorship from Wave 
 Hill curatorial staff and arts professionals\, and AnkhLave Alumni Network
  benefits. Two fellowships awarded. No application fee.\nDuration: January
  to December 2027\; Winter Workspace residency 23 February - 18 April 2027
 \; solo exhibition 15 May - 4 July 2027\n\nMore: https://wavehill.slideroo
 m.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral#/login/pr
 ogram/89300
URL:https://wavehill.slideroom.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&u
 tm_medium=referral#/login/program/89300
LOCATION:Wave Hill Public Garden and Cultural Center\, the Bronx\, New York
  City\, USA. For NYC-based BIPOC visual artists aged 30 or younger.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:james-castle-house-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260828
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260829
SUMMARY:Deadline: James Castle House: 2027 Artist Residencies (Boise\, Idah
 o)
DESCRIPTION:The James Castle House in Boise\, Idaho (the preserved home of 
 self-taught artist James Castle) opens applications for its 2027 residency
  terms from 16 July to 28 August 2026. TWO-MONTH RESIDENCY: an immersive f
 ocus on a project or body of work responding to the history and legacy of 
 James Castle or the site\; open to artists\, scholars\, creators and profe
 ssionals in any field\; $4\,000 stipend\; residents share their practice t
 hrough public events (workshops\, open studios\, presentations) and donate
  a selected piece to the City of Boise collection. Terms: 1 March - 30 Apr
 il\, 1 June - 31 July\, or 1 September - 31 October 2027. TWO-WEEK RESIDEN
 CY: time and space for a single site-responsive project\; $1\,000 stipend\
 ; one public event. Terms: 11-25 January or 1-15 December 2027. A rolling 
 PROJECT RESIDENCY also considers proposals case by case (email jamescastle
 house@cityofboise.org). ELIGIBILITY: 18+\, legally able to work in the Uni
 ted States\, able to pass a background check\; emerging and mid-career pra
 ctitioners in any field\, though the property cannot accommodate loud or e
 specially messy processes. Residents live alone on site. Selection by comm
 ittee on strength of proposal\, application\, work samples and references.
  Virtual information session 21 July 2026\, 1pm MT. Applicants notified Se
 ptember 2026. DEADLINE: 28 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: James Castle Hous
 e / City of Boise\nLocation: Boise\, Idaho\, USA. Open to applicants legal
 ly able to work in the United States.\nAward: $4\,000 stipend for two-mont
 h terms or $1\,000 for two-week terms\, to assist with living expenses and
  supplies\, plus solo live-in accommodation and studio at the historic Jam
 es Castle House. Residents donate one selected piece to the City of Boise 
 collection at the end of the term. No application fee.\nDuration: Two-mont
 h terms (1 Mar - 30 Apr\, 1 Jun - 31 Jul\, 1 Sep - 31 Oct 2027) or two-wee
 k terms (11-25 Jan and 1-15 Dec 2027)\n\nMore: https://www.jamescastlehous
 e.org/residencies/apply/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=
 referral
URL:https://www.jamescastlehouse.org/residencies/apply/?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Boise\, Idaho\, USA. Open to applicants legally able to work in th
 e United States.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nebraska-arts-council-artist-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261117
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261118
SUMMARY:Deadline: Nebraska Arts Council: Individual Artist Fellowship 2026 
 (Performing Arts)
DESCRIPTION:The Nebraska Arts Council's Individual Artist Fellowship awards
  up to $5\,000 for a one-year period to support professional development: 
 creating new work\, presentations\, training and/or research. The fellowsh
 ip rotates among three umbrella categories\; the 2026 round accepts Perfor
 ming Arts applications in theater/playwriting\, choreography\, filmmaking/
 screenwriting\, and music/sound. ELIGIBILITY: Nebraska resident for at lea
 st 24 months before application\, remaining resident during the fellowship
  year (attestation required)\; 19 or older\; not enrolled in an undergradu
 ate program in the discipline applied for (graduate and certificate progra
 ms allowed)\; applicants must be the originator of the submitted work\, no
 t an interpreter. Previous winners may reapply after three years with new 
 work if prior grant requirements were completed. SUBMISSION: artist biogra
 phy\, artist statement (name redacted\; themes\, influences\, techniques)\
 , and five work samples with descriptions or synopses. Questions: meagan.d
 ion@nebraska.gov. DEADLINE: 17 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Nebraska Ar
 ts Council\nLocation: Nebraska\, USA. Applicants must have been Nebraska r
 esidents for at least 24 months before applying and remain residents durin
 g the fellowship year.\nAward: Up to $5\,000 for a one-year fellowship sup
 porting professional development\, including the creation of new art\, pre
 sentations\, training and/or research. No application fee.\nDuration: One-
 year fellowship period\n\nMore: https://www.artscouncil.nebraska.gov/apply
 /individual-artist-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_m
 edium=referral
URL:https://www.artscouncil.nebraska.gov/apply/individual-artist-fellowship
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Nebraska\, USA. Applicants must have been Nebraska residents for a
 t least 24 months before applying and remain residents during the fellowsh
 ip year.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jcal-artworks-fellowship-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: JCAL: ARTWorks Fellowship 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:Jamaica Center for Arts and Learning (JCAL) invites New York Ci
 ty-based visual artists to apply for ARTWorks\, its Artist Fellowship Trai
 ning Seminar Series: a six-month fellowship focused on career sustainabili
 ty that amplifies the work of emerging\, underrepresented visual artists. 
 Six Fellows treat their practice as a small business\, set entrepreneurial
  and professional goals\, and build a long-term plan\, supported by a Prog
 ram Manager\, an established Artist Mentor\, cohort meetings\, and at leas
 t six seminar events (past topics: copyright and contracts\, working with 
 galleries and collectors\, grant writing\, taxes and accounting\, marketin
 g\, art handling). SUPPORT: $5\,000 per Fellow paid over the program\, fre
 e shared studio space (about 550 sq ft\, as available) with a storage clos
 et\, one free JCAL class\, and a concluding two-month group exhibition wit
 h catalogue (opens 9 April 2027). ELIGIBILITY: reside in New York City (pr
 eferably Queens) or Long Island\; identify as BIIPOC (Black\, Immigrant\, 
 Indigenous\, People of Color)\; demonstrate clarity of concept and strong 
 craft with a deep commitment to social practice\; must NOT have received m
 ajor exposure via exhibitions\, grants or residencies\; must not be enroll
 ed in any college degree or certificate program\; past Fellows ineligible.
  Priority to Queens-based artists of underrepresented communities\; multid
 isciplinary practices welcome\, but the program focuses on visual artists 
 working in traditional forms. APPLY via Submittable with six images OR two
  3-5 minute videos\, a one-page work-sample description\, artist statement
  (max 300 words)\, one professional reference (max 300 words)\, CV\, and a
  paragraph on your expectations of ARTWorks. Jury reviews submissions with
 out obvious identifiers. TIMELINE: first-round notifications 3 August 2026
 \, interviews 11-14 August\, Fellows notified 21 August\, program runs 7 O
 ctober 2026 to 18 June 2027. DEADLINE: midnight Monday 13 July 2026 (porta
 l closes 14 July 2026\, 6:00 AM ET).\n\nOrganisation: Jamaica Center for A
 rts and Learning (JCAL)\nLocation: Jamaica\, Queens\, New York City\, USA.
  Open to visual artists based in New York City (preferably Queens) or Long
  Island\; priority to Queens-based BIIPOC artists.\nAward: $5\,000 per Fel
 low\, paid out over the course of the program\, plus free shared studio sp
 ace at JCAL (about 550 sq ft\, as available)\, a 7 x 4 ft storage closet\,
  one free JCAL class (space-available)\, an Artist Mentor and seminar seri
 es\, and a concluding two-month group exhibition with catalogue in JCAL's 
 Miller and Community galleries. No application fee.\nDuration: Six-month f
 ellowship: 7 October 2026 to 18 June 2027\; exhibition opens 9 April 2027\
 n\nMore: https://jcal.submittable.com/submit/354501/artworks-fellowship-20
 26-2027?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://jcal.submittable.com/submit/354501/artworks-fellowship-2026-202
 7?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Jamaica\, Queens\, New York City\, USA. Open to visual artists bas
 ed in New York City (preferably Queens) or Long Island\; priority to Queen
 s-based BIIPOC artists.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:queer-art-design-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260814
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260815
SUMMARY:Deadline: Queer|Art Design Grant 2026 (Inaugural)
DESCRIPTION:The Queer|Art Design Grant is a new initiative from Queer|Art s
 upporting projects that explore queer histories\, legacies\, and futures w
 hile providing visibility and opportunity for emerging LGBTQ+ design talen
 t. AWARDS: two USD 10\,000 grants to emerging queer creatives across the d
 esign industry\, described as the largest cash grant for LGBTQ+ designers 
 in the country. ELIGIBILITY: US-based designers working across a variety o
 f disciplines\, including graphic design\, architecture and landscape arch
 itecture\, industrial and product design\, fashion\, textile and wearables
 \, digital design\, service design\, furniture and home decor\, materials 
 research\, interior design\, and more. In its inaugural year the grant is 
 judged by a panel of designers\, curators\, architects\, and cultural lead
 ers\, including Bex McCharen\, Salome Asega\, Cristina Grajales\, Jaffer K
 olb\, and Paul Soulellis. The program is the first major initiative under 
 a new partnership between UGG and Queer|Art\; Queer|Art board member and c
 reative strategist Fran Tirado serves as Community Curator. Winners will b
 e announced at Queer|Art's Annual Party in Fall 2026. DEADLINE: 14 August 
 2026. Apply via https://www.queer-art.org/design-grant.\n\nOrganisation: Q
 ueer|Art (in partnership with UGG)\nLocation: United States\; open to US-b
 ased emerging queer/LGBTQ+ designers.\nAward: Two USD 10\,000 grants (desc
 ribed as the largest cash grant for LGBTQ+ designers in the US). No applic
 ation fee.\nDuration: One-off grant\; winners announced at Queer|Art's Ann
 ual Party\, Fall 2026\n\nMore: https://www.queer-art.org/design-grant?utm_
 source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.queer-art.org/design-grant?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States\; open to US-based emerging queer/LGBTQ+ designers.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:alabama-clotilda-memorial-public-art-commission-2026@artificialnouveau.
 github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260809
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260810
SUMMARY:Deadline: Alabama Historical Commission: Clotilda Memorial Public A
 rt Commission
DESCRIPTION:The Alabama Historical Commission\, working with public-art con
 sultancy Forecast Public Art\, seeks proposals for a major memorial artwor
 k honoring the survivors of the Clotilda\, the last known ship to illegall
 y traffic enslaved Africans to the United States (1860). The memorial will
  convey the survivors' lives and legacies and be developed through collabo
 rative community engagement with historic Africatown\, the community found
 ed by Clotilda survivors\, and the broader diaspora. ELIGIBILITY: open to 
 artists of all disciplines\, including time-based and media artists\; indi
 viduals and teams\; open internationally. BUDGET: USD 2\,000\,000 total pr
 oject budget. DEADLINE: 9 August 2026\, 11:59pm CST. Applications are hand
 led through the CODAworx RFQ platform\; find the Clotilda Memorial listing
  in the CODAworx opportunities index. Verify the listing details on CODAwo
 rx before applying.\n\nOrganisation: Alabama Historical Commission (with F
 orecast Public Art)\nLocation: Africatown\, Mobile\, Alabama\, USA\; open 
 to artists internationally.\nAward: USD 2\,000\,000 total project budget f
 or a paid public art commission. No application fee.\nDuration: Permanent 
 public art commission\n\nMore: https://www.codaworx.com/rfp/?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.codaworx.com/rfp/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm
 _medium=referral
LOCATION:Africatown\, Mobile\, Alabama\, USA\; open to artists internationa
 lly.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:dadalab-extreme-heat-exhibition-austin-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260703
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260704
SUMMARY:Deadline: dadalab: Extreme Heat Exhibition (Call for Artists)
DESCRIPTION:dadalab is seeking three Austin-based BIPOC artists to create o
 riginal works exploring extreme heat through the lenses of science\, publi
 c health and labor. The open call is medium-agnostic and welcomes work in 
 any format. The goal is to bring awareness to environmental justice and th
 e impact of extreme heat in Austin. AWARD: each selected artist receives a
  USD 2\,000 artist fee plus a supply stipend. The resulting works are show
 n in a two-day exhibition on 3-4 October 2026 at dadalab in East Austin. E
 LIGIBILITY: open to Austin-based BIPOC artists working in any medium. Appl
 ication deadline 3 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: dadalab\nLocation: Austin\,
  Texas\, United States (East Austin). Open to Austin-based BIPOC artists.\
 nAward: USD 2\,000 artist fee plus a supply stipend. Three artists selecte
 d.\nDuration: Create original work for a two-day exhibition\, 3-4 October 
 2026.\n\nMore: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Pad_gI333_X9tcBfe5DD0fX
 737PZ6zY0CzecyBfo9a4/edit?usp=sharing&utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdes
 k&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Pad_gI333_X9tcBfe5DD0fX737PZ6zY0Cze
 cyBfo9a4/edit?usp=sharing&utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium
 =referral
LOCATION:Austin\, Texas\, United States (East Austin). Open to Austin-based
  BIPOC artists.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-us-ai-policy-program-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program
DESCRIPTION:The GovAI U.S. AI Policy Program is a bipartisan\, part-time\, 
 12-week program designed to accelerate or launch careers in U.S. AI policy
 . Open to U.S. policy professionals across government and think tanks\, it
  builds a technically-informed understanding of the AI policy landscape th
 rough guided discussion sessions\, with an emphasis on general-purpose AI.
  Topics include how general-purpose AI systems are developed\; inputs to A
 I development such as energy\, chips\, and data centers\; AI's effects on 
 productivity\, scientific discovery\, and economic growth\; national secur
 ity and great power competition\; corporate self-governance\; AI regulatio
 n in other jurisdictions\; and federal and state AI regulatory proposals i
 n the U.S. Participants also have weekly opportunities to question world-l
 eading experts\; prior guest speakers have included White House OSTP staff
 ers\, former frontier-lab employees\, and people who helped draft U.S. sta
 te- and federal-level AI policy proposals. The program runs early Septembe
 r to early December 2026 (break for Thanksgiving week) with a roughly 5-ho
 ur weekly commitment: two hours of synchronous evening sessions (EST)\, he
 ld in-person at GovAI's D.C. office near DuPont Circle or remotely with ca
 meras on\, plus three hours of independent reading and podcasts from a fre
 e syllabus. To list completion on a resume\, participants must attend 9 of
  12 sessions\, write a short policy memo or op-ed\, and pass an interview-
 based exam. Eligible participants include executive and legislative branch
  staff (fellows\, interns\, detailees\, military personnel\, national labo
 ratory personnel) and think-tank policy researchers and affiliates\, acros
 s a range of seniority levels\, with preference for the D.C. metropolitan 
 area\; participants need not currently cover AI but should aspire to a car
 eer in U.S. tech or national security policy. Selection has two stages: an
  online application with six biographical questions\, a resume\, two verba
 l reasoning questions\, and an approximately 7-minute video\; followed by 
 a 30-minute interview in July\, with final decisions in early August.\n\nO
 rganisation: Centre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: Washington
 \, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)\nAward: Free to pa
 rticipate\; in-person attendees provided dinner (value kept at or below US
 D 20 per session)\nDuration: 12-week part-time program\, early September t
 o early December 2026 (approximately 5 hours per week)\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/govai-u-s-ai-policy-program?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Washington\, D.C.\, USA (hybrid\; remote participation available)
END:VEVENT
