 o
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261231
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270101
SUMMARY:Deadline: Farm\, Flock and Fiber Artist in Residence
DESCRIPTION:A Wrinkle in Thyme Farm is a small\, women-owned diversified fa
 rm in Sumner\, Maine that offers a six-month live-in fiber arts residency 
 starting in May. The resident exchanges an average of 15 to 20 hours per w
 eek of farm work for a modest monthly stipend\, free private rustic housin
 g\, community meals\, farm-grown food\, and access to the fiber studio. Re
 sidents receive solo studio time plus one day a week of learning and colla
 boration with fiber artist Marty Elkin\, working with home-grown Maine woo
 l through felting\, dyeing\, knitting and spinning. The program also inclu
 des training in flock management\, animal husbandry and lamb care\, with t
 he option to add two months for lambing season. It is designed for emergin
 g fiber artists who are single females able to lift 50 pounds and work aro
 und a farm. Applications open in November with a December 31 deadline and 
 a non-refundable USD 25 application fee.\n\nOrganisation: A Wrinkle in Thy
 me Farm\nLocation: Sumner\, Maine\, USA\nAward: Modest monthly stipend (ar
 ound USD 400/month) in exchange for roughly 15 to 20 hours/week of farm wo
 rk\, plus free rustic private housing (solar power\, wood stove)\, shared 
 kitchen\, bath and WiFi\, community meals and farm-grown food\, dedicated 
 solo studio time\, and weekly collaboration with resident fiber artist Mar
 ty Elkin. USD 25 non-refundable application fee\nDuration: Six months begi
 nning in May\, with an optional two additional months for lambing and earl
 y lamb care\n\nMore: https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294&utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294&utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Sumner\, Maine\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:helene-wurlitzer-foundation-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270118
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270119
SUMMARY:Deadline: Helene Wurlitzer Foundation Residency
DESCRIPTION:The Helene Wurlitzer Foundation of New Mexico runs one of the o
 ldest artist residency programs in the United States\, established in 1954
 \, on a 15-acre campus in Taos\, New Mexico. The residency is open to visu
 al artists\, literary artists\, and music composers\, including painters\,
  sculptors\, photographers\, filmmakers\, writers\, poets\, playwrights\, 
 screenwriters\, and songwriters. Selected grantees receive rent-free and u
 tility-paid housing in a furnished casita for a session of 10 to 12 weeks\
 , with access to a Commons House offering WiFi\, a library\, and bicycles.
  No stipend is provided in most cases\, and residents cover their own food
  and transportation. Applications are open to creative artists worldwide r
 egardless of age\, experience\, or nationality\, and the annual deadline i
 s January 18 for residencies the following calendar year. There is a non-w
 aivable USD 30 application fee.\n\nOrganisation: The Helene Wurlitzer Foun
 dation of New Mexico\nLocation: Taos\, New Mexico\, USA\nAward: Rent-free\
 , utility-paid furnished housing (casita)\; no stipend (rare stipend suppo
 rt via the Rhonda Artist Stipend Fund)\; artists cover food and travel USD
  30 application fee\nDuration: 10 to 12 weeks (Sessions 1 and 3 are 12 wee
 ks\, Session 2 is 10 weeks)\n\nMore: https://wurlitzerfoundation.org/apply
 ?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://wurlitzerfoundation.org/apply?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Taos\, New Mexico\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kala-fellowship-program-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270301
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270302
SUMMARY:Deadline: Kala Fellowship Program
DESCRIPTION:The Kala Fellowship Program supports international\, national\,
  and local artists producing innovative work in and across multiple media\
 , with an emphasis on Kala's specialized printmaking\, photography\, and d
 igital media equipment. The institute supports up to 6 artists per cycle w
 ith a USD 3\,000 stipend\, 24/7 access to its Berkeley facilities for 1 to
  9 months\, one month of housing for artists based outside the 9 Bay Area 
 counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a culminating group show in the 
 Kala Gallery. Applications are submitted through kala.slideroom.com and re
 quire a statement of interest\, an artist CV\, documentation of 5 to 10 re
 cent works\, and two references. Artists enrolled in a degree-granting pro
 gram during the fellowship period are not eligible. The application opens 
 in December with no fee through January 15\, after which a USD 25 applicat
 ion fee applies through the March 1 deadline.\n\nOrganisation: Kala Art In
 stitute\nLocation: Berkeley\, California\, USA\nAward: USD 3\,000 stipend\
 , 24/7 facility access for 1 to 9 months\, 1 month of housing for artists 
 outside the 9 Bay Area counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a group e
 xhibition USD 25 application fee (free if applying December through Januar
 y 15)\nDuration: 1 to 9 months within the July 2026 to June 2027 fellowshi
 p period\n\nMore: https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/?utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/?utm_source=artific
 ialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Berkeley\, California\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:roswell-artist-in-residence-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270315
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270316
SUMMARY:Deadline: Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program
DESCRIPTION:The Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program\, established in 1967 a
 nd run by The RAiR Foundation\, offers visual artists a year-long studio-b
 ased residency known as the Gift of Time. Each resident receives a private
  house and a studio on a fifty-acre complex\, with rent\, utilities\, repa
 irs\, and maintenance covered by the program. Artists also receive a month
 ly stipend of USD 1\,100 plus a USD 250 monthly materials stipend. The pro
 gram is open to professional visual artists aged 21 and older working in p
 ainting\, drawing\, sculpture\, printmaking\, photography\, video\, digita
 l media\, and installation. It does not support performance art\, writing\
 , music\, or production crafts. The application period for the next cycle 
 runs from January 1 to March 15\, 2027\, and international applicants are 
 accepted with visa support available.\n\nOrganisation: The RAiR Foundation
 \nLocation: Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA\nAward: USD 1\,100 per month stipen
 d\, plus USD 250 per month materials stipend from the Frederick Hammersley
  Foundation. Includes a private house and a studio with rent\, utilities\,
  repairs\, and maintenance covered. USD 26.32 application fee\nDuration: 1
 2 months (one year)\n\nMore: https://www.rair.org/application-info?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.rair.org/application-info?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wassaic-project-2027-summer-exhibition-open-call@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260810
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260811
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wassaic Project 2027 Summer Exhibition Open Call
DESCRIPTION:The Wassaic Project is holding its annual Open Call for the 202
 7 Summer Exhibition\, for artists of all mediums\, including 2D work\, scu
 lpture\, video\, new media\, site-specific installation\, performance\, te
 xt\, poems\, essays\, and publication-specific work. Selected work is show
 cased alongside a diverse range of pieces and performances in and around h
 istoric Wassaic and Maxon Mills\; the 2027 Summer Exhibition will be free 
 and open to the public every weekend from 1 May to 12 September 2027. In a
 n effort toward W.A.G.E. certification\, all accepted artists receive a mo
 dest honorarium to participate. Artists interested in creating a site-spec
 ific installation are also eligible for an Exhibitions Fellowship to help 
 realize their work\; Fellows are offered a no-fee residency for 1-4 weeks 
 in April or May 2027 (artists interested in making site-specific work shou
 ld still apply regardless of whether they are interested in or able to be 
 in residence). The Wassaic Project cultivates and supports community for e
 merging and professional contemporary artists\, writers\, and other creati
 ves\, with a residency program housed in historic landmark buildings that 
 hosts 10 artists each month in the heart of a rural community. APPLICATION
 : requires application forms\, a CV\, and an artwork/portfolio\; submitted
  via SlideRoom. Application fee: USD 25 (no participation fee or additiona
 l fees). Deadline 10 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: The Wassaic Project\nLo
 cation: Wassaic\, New York\, United States (in and around historic Wassaic
  and Maxon Mills).\nAward: A modest honorarium for all accepted artists (p
 art of the organization's effort toward W.A.G.E. certification). Artists c
 reating site-specific installations are also eligible for an Exhibitions F
 ellowship and a no-fee residency of 1-4 weeks in April or May 2027.\nDurat
 ion: The 2027 Summer Exhibition runs free and open to the public every wee
 kend\, 1 May to 12 September 2027. Optional fellowship residency of 1-4 we
 eks in April or May 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply/su
 mmer-exhibition-faq?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply/summer-exhibition-faq?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Wassaic\, New York\, United States (in and around historic Wassaic
  and Maxon Mills).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:atu-windgate-artist-in-residence-fall-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260703
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260704
SUMMARY:Deadline: Windgate Artist-in-Residence Fall 2026 (Arkansas Tech Uni
 versity)
DESCRIPTION:The Artist-in-Residence (AIR) program at Arkansas Tech Universi
 ty is an immersive experience within an art and educational community\, in
 tended to advance the careers of practicing artists\, present residents as
  role models for the ATU community\, and strengthen public awareness of th
 e significance of making art and its effect on the surrounding community. 
 The residency takes place over a five-month period\, giving the artist tim
 e and space to focus on the creative process. For Fall 2026\, the program 
 will select an artist to create a public artwork that enhances the ATU cam
 pus\; both two-dimensional and three-dimensional proposals will be conside
 red. The program is supported by a generous grant from the Windgate Charit
 able Foundation. The Department of Art at ATU offers programs in Fine Art\
 , Graphic Design\, Game and Interactive Media Design\, and Art Education\,
  with a facility in Norman Hall featuring a professional gallery\, compute
 r lab\, lecture hall\, and studios for painting\, drawing\, printmaking\, 
 sculpture\, ceramics\, and graphic design. RESIDENCY DETAILS & EXPECTATION
 S: residents must be artists with significant exhibition records\, strong 
 communication skills\, sustained studio practice\, and a desire to engage 
 with the larger campus community\; involvement may include guest lecturing
 \, public talks\, mentoring students\, open studios\, and/or collaborating
  with faculty and students. The resident sometimes teaches one course in 2
 D Design\, 3D Design\, or Introduction to Drawing during their stay when e
 nrollment allows. Artists are expected to commit as a full-time resident f
 or the Fall academic term 2026. BENEFITS: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fring
 es)\, USD 18\,000 for supplies\, a 2-bed/2-bath campus apartment\, and a l
 arge climate-controlled off-campus studio. Deadline 3 July 2026.\n\nOrgani
 sation: Arkansas Tech University (supported by the Windgate Charitable Fou
 ndation)\nLocation: Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville 
 campus\, in the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). 
 In-person\, full-time residency.\nAward: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fringe
 s) plus USD 18\,000 for supplies. Housing provided (a 2-bed\, 2-bath campu
 s apartment) and a large\, climate-controlled\, dedicated off-campus studi
 o space.\nDuration: Five-month residency over the Fall academic term 2026.
 \n\nMore: https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20A
 D%20FALL%202026.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20AD%20FAL
 L%202026.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville campus\, in 
 the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). In-person\, 
 full-time residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:creative-philadelphia-msb-interpretive-panels-2026@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: MSB Interpretive Panels: Public Art Commission (Creative 
 Philadelphia)
DESCRIPTION:Creative Philadelphia announces a call to commission a series o
 f permanent interpretive panels with integrated augmented reality (AR) com
 ponents at the Municipal Services Building in Center City Philadelphia. Th
 e commission is part of a broader initiative that includes an upcoming pub
 lic sculpture of Dr. Sadie T.M. Alexander by artist Vinnie Bagwell. Inspir
 ed by Alexander's groundbreaking legacy in public service\, these interpre
 tive panels will celebrate the City of Philadelphia's municipal employees 
 (past\, present\, and future) and provide deeper context for understanding
  Dr. Alexander's impact\; they will be located in front of the building's 
 landscaped areas\, flanking the upcoming sculpture\, and are intended to c
 omplement and support the overall site experience. SCOPE: an artist team w
 ill design and fabricate four (4) permanent\, sculptural interpretive pane
 ls incorporating augmented reality (AR) elements to expand storytelling be
 yond the physical surface of the artwork. ELIGIBILITY: all interested arti
 sts are invited to apply\; Philadelphia-based artists are strongly encoura
 ged\, though artists from outside the region will be considered\; multiple
  in-person site visits are required and associated travel costs must be co
 vered within the project budget. SELECTION: a two-part process: Part 1 sub
 mission of qualifications\; Part 2 finalist proposals and interviews. Up t
 o three (3) finalists are invited to submit short concept proposals and at
 tend an interview\; at no point should artists submit design proposals. BU
 DGET: USD 250\,000 total (see amount for the required cost breakdown). An 
 Artist Informational Meeting is held via Zoom on 30 June\, 6:00-7:00pm. Ap
 plication questions: paige.phillips@phila.gov. Apply via Submittable. Dead
 line 12 July 2026 (submissions close Monday 13 July 2026\, 6:00 AM).\n\nOr
 ganisation: Creative Philadelphia (Office of Arts\, Culture and the Creati
 ve Economy)\nLocation: Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philade
 lphia\, Pennsylvania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly 
 encouraged\; artists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-perso
 n site visits required (travel costs covered within the project budget).\n
 Award: Total project budget of USD 250\,000\, which must cover: artist fee
 s (18% design fee)\, design and engineering\, fabrication and installation
 \, structural footings/anchoring\, travel and site visits\, AR development
  (software\, hosting\, content production)\, insurance (1%)\, community en
 gagement participation\, and a service warranty keeping content compatible
  with new mobile OS versions for a minimum of 10 years. No application fee
 s.\nDuration: Permanent public artwork commission\; two-part selection pro
 cess.\n\nMore: https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretiv
 e-panels?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretive-panels?utm
 _source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philadelphia\, Pennsyl
 vania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly encouraged\; ar
 tists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-person site visits r
 equired (travel costs covered within the project budget).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:neiu-art-design-studio-art-residency-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260809
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260810
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:The NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency strives to create vi
 sible connections between Northeastern Illinois University's diverse popul
 ation of art and design students and working artists who embody these iden
 tities\, providing insights and inspiration through a dynamic exchange of 
 ideas and techniques. Visiting Artists should demonstrate a commitment to 
 their artistic practice and an interest in engaging with NEIU's students a
 nd creative community. Each Visiting Artist is awarded an honorarium and h
 as full access for a semester to the NEIU Art + Design facilities specific
  to their project\; over the residency they showcase their work in a publi
 c academic forum\, lead a hands-on workshop\, and participate in a Portfol
 io Review Day for NEIU's Art + Design students. FACILITIES (in the Salme H
 arju Steinberg Fine Arts Center) include a Design Studio with the largest 
 collection of Riso drums at any Chicago university\, a Fab Lab (FDM and re
 sin 3D printers\, large-format CNC router\, vinyl cutters\, laser cutters)
 \, a Ceramic Studio (throwing wheels\, glaze room\, electric and gas kilns
 \, raku area)\, a Letterpress Studio (two Vandercook presses\, metal and w
 ood type)\, a Sculpture Studio (wood shop\, clay modeling and spray painti
 ng areas)\, a Photography Studio (analog and digital\, plus a lighting stu
 dio)\, and fully equipped Painting\, Drawing\, and Printmaking studios. BE
 NEFITS: USD 800 honorarium\; facility access based on project focus (Art +
  Tech\, Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpt
 ure)\, with supplies requestable subject to approval\; and the opportunity
  to exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEIU Fine Arts Center Gallery. PA
 RTICIPATION: lead a 2-hour hands-on workshop for 15-20 students on a topic
  relevant to the project\; give an hour-long artist talk with Q&A\; and se
 rve as a guest panelist for a day-long portfolio review. KEY DATES: open c
 all 2 June - 9 August\; emailed acceptances in October\; Residency Session
  1 runs 25 January - 14 May and Session 2 runs 30 August - 11 December. Ap
 ply via the JotForm application. Deadline 9 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Northeastern Illinois University (NEIU)\, Art + Design Department\nLocatio
 n: Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Universi
 ty\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long access 
 to NEIU facilities.\nAward: USD 800 honorarium\, plus a semester of full a
 ccess to NEIU Art + Design facilities specific to the project (Art + Tech\
 , Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpture)\;
  supplies can be requested with guidance and approval from Studio Area per
 sonnel. Visiting Artists may also exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEI
 U Fine Arts Center Gallery.\nDuration: One semester. Residency Session 1: 
 25 January - 14 May\; Session 2: 30 August - 11 December.\n\nMore: https:/
 /form.jotform.com/261044627286156?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral
URL:https://form.jotform.com/261044627286156?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Uni
 versity\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long ac
 cess to NEIU facilities.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:art-shanty-projects-performances-art-actions-2027@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: Art Shanty Projects 2027: Call for Performances + Art Act
 ions
DESCRIPTION:Art Shanty Projects seeks winter enthusiasts and creative adven
 turers to create performances and art actions for its 2027 Program on Bde 
 Uman (Lake Harriet) in Minneapolis. It invites music-makers\, poets\, buil
 ders\, scientists\, dancers\, puppeteers\, writers\, dreamers\, activists\
 , outdoors-people\, conversationalists\, craftspeople\, storytellers\, and
  more to propose new and innovative ways to engage artistically with the p
 ublic in the social context of a village on a frozen lake (or winter 'beac
 h'\, as climate change may necessitate). ASP has an expansive notion of wh
 at constitutes a performance or art action\, having welcomed dance\, creat
 ive sporting events\, happenings\, carnival games\, music\, roving dance\,
  temporary sculpture\, puppet shows\, artful haircuts\, advice booths\, cl
 imate actions\, and more. NOTE: this call is for PERFORMANCES + ART ACTION
 S only (a separate call exists for shanty artists). Since 2004\, Art Shant
 y Projects has created joyful winter art experiences inspired by pop-up ic
 e fishing villages\, using the frozen lake as a public platform for a temp
 orary creative community with tens of thousands of annual visitors. ASP is
  deeply committed to social\, racial\, gender\, and economic justice and t
 o accessibility (embracing the spirit of the ADA). ELIGIBILITY: everyone i
 s eligible (artists at all career stages)\; applicants need not have exper
 ience with everything asked\, but should show eagerness to engage\, develo
 p new skills\, and stay open to new perspectives. Projects that involve se
 lling anything or the exchange of legal currency will not be accepted. COM
 PENSATION: sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 plus extensive productio
 n and logistical support. PROGRAM: on-ice every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am
 -4pm\, 16 January to 7 February 2027\; selected artists notified mid-Augus
 t 2026\, with mandatory in-person meetings (at least one team member) star
 ting 10 September 2026. Apply via the Google form (preferred) or the no-Go
 ogle-account alternative. Contact Erin Lavelle\, Artistic Director: progra
 m@artshantyprojects.org. Deadline for proposal submissions: 9 July 2026\, 
 11:59pm CST.\n\nOrganisation: Art Shanty Projects\nLocation: Bde Uman (Lak
 e Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States. On-ice program plus 
 several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\; in-person participat
 ion required.\nAward: Sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 (request an a
 mount that fits the project: roughly USD 1\,000 for full-day/most-ambitiou
 s activities\, USD 500 for half-day\, USD 250 for short or one-off/solo/lo
 w-production activities). Plus direct production support\, discounted mate
 rials and resource sharing\, a shared warming shanty\, a hot meal\, snacks
 \, hot beverages\, hand/toe warmers\, one parking space per project\, on-s
 ite medic\, and ASL interpreter/audio describer for the public. No applica
 tion fees.\nDuration: On-ice program every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am-4pm\
 , 16 January to 7 February 2027\, with production meetings and mandatory c
 heck-ins from September 2026 onward.\n\nMore: https://artshantyprojects.or
 g/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://artshantyprojects.org/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/?u
 tm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Bde Uman (Lake Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States.
  On-ice program plus several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\;
  in-person participation required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:justice-joy-summer-research-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: Justice + Joy Summer Research Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Justice + Joy Research Fellowship is a seven-week virtual s
 ummer program for girls\, young women\, and gender-expansive young people 
 of color (ages 18-26) in the United States who want to explore issues impa
 cting their lives\, communities\, and futures. Fellows identify a topic th
 ey care about\, such as mental health\, education\, reproductive justice\,
  immigration\, AI and technology\, gender-based violence\, beauty standard
 s\, young parenthood\, or another issue affecting their communities\, and 
 develop an original research project grounded in their experiences\, quest
 ions\, and ideas. Throughout the summer\, fellows participate in weekly vi
 rtual sessions\, engage with guest speakers\, build community with peers f
 rom across the country\, and receive mentorship and support as they develo
 p their research. The fellowship culminates in a capstone showcase where f
 ellows present their work to the Justice + Joy community\, including organ
 izational leaders\, partners\, and supporters. No prior research experienc
 e is required\; the program seeks young people who are curious\, committed
  to learning\, and interested in using research as a tool for understandin
 g\, advocacy\, and change. COMMITMENT: weekly virtual sessions on Wednesda
 ys 5:00-6:30 PM ET (9 July - 20 August 2026)\; approximately 2-4 hours of 
 independent work per week\; required orientation on Wednesday 9 July\; dev
 elopment of an individual research proposal or conceptual framework\; pres
 entation at the capstone showcase (tentatively in person\, mid-September 2
 026\, with all travel and lodging covered). WHAT YOU GET: a USD 2\,000 sti
 pend paid upon successful completion\; skills-based training in research m
 ethods\, social justice frameworks\, and community advocacy\; guest speake
 r sessions\; a peer community\; and a real audience for the research (the 
 Justice + Joy board and funders). Apply via the Google Form. Note: an expl
 icit application deadline is not stated\; the required orientation and pro
 gram start is 9 July 2026\, so apply before then.\n\nOrganisation: Justice
  + Joy\nLocation: United States\; fully virtual program. Capstone showcase
  tentatively in person (mid-September 2026)\, with travel and lodging cove
 red.\nAward: USD 2\,000 stipend paid upon successful program completion\, 
 plus skills-based training\, guest speaker sessions\, and peer community. 
 All travel and lodging for the in-person capstone are covered.\nDuration: 
 Seven-week virtual program\, 9 July to 20 August 2026\, with a capstone sh
 owcase mid-September 2026. Weekly Wednesday sessions 5:00-6:30 PM ET plus 
 approximately 2-4 hours of independent work per week.\n\nMore: https://doc
 s.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfXN_oqSA7G7RRPjhLp-_McFix70m4g8Q_yny0aiBDb-
 qfHvw/viewform?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfXN_oqSA7G7RRPjhLp-_McFix70m4
 g8Q_yny0aiBDb-qfHvw/viewform?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_med
 ium=referral
LOCATION:United States\; fully virtual program. Capstone showcase tentative
 ly in person (mid-September 2026)\, with travel and lodging covered.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:genesis-mission-ai-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Genesis Mission AI Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Horizon Institute for Public Service\, Renaissance Philanth
 ropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science are partnering to launch a fellowship 
 that embeds technical AI talent across the US Department of Energy nationa
 l labs to advance the goals of the Genesis Mission\, DOE's flagship scienc
 e and technology initiative launched in late 2025. The Genesis Mission ide
 ntifies 26 national science and technology challenges critical to US leade
 rship and envisions a national platform connecting supercomputers\, experi
 mental facilities\, AI systems\, and unique datasets\, with DOE's 17 natio
 nal labs playing a key role. Genesis Mission AI Fellows are forward deploy
 ed to DOE national labs to bring frontier AI expertise to high-priority sc
 ientific challenges. As core members of the technical staff on a Genesis M
 ission project\, fellows work alongside national lab scientists and partne
 rs and apply AI to national priorities\, from building cutting-edge models
  of plasma dynamics in pursuit of controlled fusion to advancing state-of-
 the-art models for foundational materials discovery. Initial national lab 
 partners include Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National Laborator
 y\, and the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory\; additional partners may 
 be announced later. COMPENSATION/DURATION: 9-12 months starting fall 2026\
 , with a prorated total annual compensation of USD 200\,000\; fellows are 
 expected to travel to their national lab site at least once a quarter but 
 may work on-site if they prefer. ELIGIBILITY: competitive applicants shoul
 d have at least 2 years of industry experience building AI models or agent
 s (those with industry experience building AI applications or data infrast
 ructure will also be considered)\; scientific domain expertise is not requ
 ired\, but any placement will involve some training and study in a specifi
 c scientific discipline or energy topic\, supported by expert colleagues a
 t the host institution. All fellows must be eligible to work in the United
  States for the duration of the placement\; US employment visas cannot be 
 sponsored\, but US permanent residents (green card holders) are eligible. 
 APPLICATION: initial form requires a CV or resume (max 2 pages) and short-
 answer questions on motivations and experiences (max 200 words)\; successf
 ul applicants complete interviews through partner organizations and nation
 al labs\, and selected fellows are matched to partner labs by scientific d
 omain and availability. The review uses evidence-based best practices incl
 uding blind grading of application materials. TIMELINE: application deadli
 ne 31 July 2026\; final fellow selection August-September 2026\; expected 
 start fall 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Horizon Institute for Public Service (wi
 th Renaissance Philanthropy\, SeedAI\, and Fulcrum Science)\nLocation: Uni
 ted States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of Energy nation
 al labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhaven National
  Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or in-person\; 
 on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to work in the US
  (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).\nAward: Prorated 
 total annual compensation of USD 200\,000.\nDuration: 9-12 months\, starti
 ng fall 2026.\n\nMore: https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-gen
 esis-mission-ai-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://horizonpublicservice.org/announcing-the-genesis-mission-ai-fell
 owship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. Fellows are forward deployed to US Department of En
 ergy national labs (initial partners: Idaho National Laboratory\, Brookhav
 en National Laboratory\, Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory). Remote or i
 n-person\; on-site travel at least once a quarter. Must be eligible to wor
 k in the US (no visa sponsorship\; US green card holders eligible).
END:VEVENT
