UID:queens-museum-qm-jerome-emerging-artist-fellowship-2027-2028@artificial
 nouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260928
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260929
SUMMARY:Deadline: Queens Museum: QM-Jerome Foundation Fellowship for Emergi
 ng Artists 2027-2028
DESCRIPTION:The QM-Jerome Foundation Fellowship for Emerging Artists select
 s two emerging visual artists living in New York City for its 2027-2028 co
 hort. Each fellow receives a $20\,000 award\, professional development con
 sultations\, mentorship from Queens Museum staff and an established New Yo
 rk-based artist\, and a solo exhibition at the Queens Museum in 2028\, wit
 h curatorial support across a full year of project development. Aimed at e
 arly-career visual artists (roughly two to ten years of professional pract
 ice) who have a consistent practice and developing public profile but have
  not yet reached major institutional recognition. ELIGIBILITY: must curren
 tly reside in one of NYC's five boroughs and maintain residency through th
 e fellowship\; artists enrolled in degree-granting programs are not eligib
 le\; review the detailed criteria on exhibition history\, previous grants 
 and years of practice. Supported by the Jerome Foundation. Apply via the Q
 ueens Museum fellowship program page. Deadline: 28 September 2026\, 11:59 
 PM EST.\n\nOrganisation: Queens Museum (with the Jerome Foundation)\nLocat
 ion: Queens\, New York City\, USA\nAward: $20\,000 fellowship award per ar
 tist (two artists selected)\, plus professional development consultations\
 , mentorship from Queens Museum staff and an established New York-based ar
 tist\, and a solo exhibition at the Queens Museum in 2028. No application 
 fee.\nDuration: One-year fellowship (2027-2028)\, culminating in a 2028 so
 lo exhibition\n\nMore: https://queensmuseum.org/fellowship/?utm_source=art
 ificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://queensmuseum.org/fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Queens\, New York City\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pandora-short-film-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261001
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261002
SUMMARY:Deadline: Pandora Short Film Grant 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Pandora Short Film Grant is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit that awar
 ds an annual $12\,000 grant to an early-career US filmmaker for the produc
 tion of a narrative short film. Projects at script stage or already filmed
  and seeking finishing funds are both eligible. The winner also receives a
  Panavision camera package (about $15\,000)\, an optional $1\,000 Kodak Fi
 lm Grant\, mentorship from an award-winning filmmaker (2026 mentors includ
 e Alma Har'el\, Lila Neugebauer\, Lauren Wolkstein\, Sarah Elizabeth Mintz
  and Chris Merola)\, and fiscal sponsorship\; three finalists receive ment
 orship\, fiscal sponsorship\, Panavision New Filmmaker Program considerati
 on and discounted production insurance. ELIGIBILITY: open to all early-car
 eer US filmmakers\; applicants are asked NOT to apply if they have directe
 d a feature film with a budget over $250K or directed or produced televisi
 on. Selection is blind\, based on script and pitch materials\, weighting a
 rtistic vision over industry resume. TIMELINE: submissions open 30 May 202
 6\, close 1 October 2026\, notifications 15 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation
 : Pandora Short Film Grant\nLocation: United States (early-career US filmm
 akers)\nAward: $12\,000 production grant to the winner\, plus a Panavision
  camera package (worth about $15\,000)\, an optional $1\,000 Kodak Film Gr
 ant toward film stock and lab expenses\, mentorship from an award-winning 
 filmmaker\, and fiscal sponsorship. Three finalists receive mentorship\, f
 iscal sponsorship\, consideration for the Panavision New Filmmaker Program
 \, and $500 off Athos production insurance. ENTRY FEE: tiered\, $30 regula
 r ($27 Gold members) and $40 late ($36)\; Pandora states fee waivers are a
 vailable on request.\nDuration: Production grant for a narrative short fil
 m (script stage or finishing funds)\n\nMore: https://pandora.org/?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://pandora.org/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
LOCATION:United States (early-career US filmmakers)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:moorhead-call-public-art-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260904
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260905
SUMMARY:Deadline: City of Moorhead: 2026 Call for Public Art (Movable Inter
 active Piece)
DESCRIPTION:The City of Moorhead is seeking proposals for an inspirational\
 , movable public artwork to be installed at rotating locations across the 
 city. Interactive elements are explicitly encouraged\, with kinetic sculpt
 ure\, digital installation and tactile elements named as examples. Strong 
 proposals invite public participation\, promote creativity and youth engag
 ement\, are safe for all members of the public\, are durable enough for ye
 ar-round outdoor conditions\, and draw people to gather. Submissions are r
 eviewed and ranked by the Artist Review Team\, whose recommendation passes
  to the Art and Culture Commission and then to City Council for the final 
 decision. Questions go to art@moorheadmn.gov. Proposals are due by 10:00am
  on Friday 4 September 2026.\n\nOrganisation: City of Moorhead\, Minnesota
 \nLocation: Moorhead\, Minnesota\, USA. The piece will be sited at differe
 nt locations throughout the city. No geographic eligibility restriction is
  stated in the call\, so non-US artists appear eligible\, but this is not 
 confirmed in writing.\nAward: Not published. The call announcement states 
 no budget\, commission amount or artist fee\, and the linked Request for A
 rt document could not be retrieved. Confirm the budget with art@moorheadmn
 .gov before investing time in a proposal. No application fee is mentioned.
 \nDuration: Single commission\; timeline not published\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.moorheadmn.gov/news/posts/2026-call-for-public-art/?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.moorheadmn.gov/news/posts/2026-call-for-public-art/?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Moorhead\, Minnesota\, USA. The piece will be sited at different l
 ocations throughout the city. No geographic eligibility restriction is sta
 ted in the call\, so non-US artists appear eligible\, but this is not conf
 irmed in writing.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bloedel-reserve-creative-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Creative Residency at Bloedel Reserve: Class of 2027
DESCRIPTION:Bloedel Reserve's residency programme exists to foster creative
  thinking inspired by nature and to explore the connection between humans 
 and the environment. It is open to professional and emerging artists\, com
 posers\, writers\, botanists\, landscape architects\, researchers and othe
 rs working on themes of nature and human connection to it. Residents get a
  three-week stay at a 140-acre internationally recognised public garden an
 d forest preserve\, housed in a small home hidden in the woods off the mai
 n paths. Note for non-US applicants: the funding is structured as expense 
 reimbursement rather than a stipend\, capped at USD 1\,000\, which for tra
 nsatlantic applicants is unlikely to cover airfare plus meals over three w
 eeks.\n\nOrganisation: Bloedel Reserve\nLocation: Bainbridge Island\, Wash
 ington\, USA\, between Seattle and the Kitsap Peninsula\, reachable by fer
 ry from Seattle or by car via the Kitsap Peninsula. Residents must be 21 o
 r older. International applicants are eligible but are funded differently 
 from domestic ones (see amount).\nAward: USD 22 application fee. Furnished
  private house on the grounds with linens\, stocked kitchen\, wi-fi\, laun
 dry and use of a smart car\; an electric piano is available. Domestic resi
 dents receive a USD 1\,000 stipend. International residents receive no sti
 pend and may instead submit up to USD 1\,000 of expenses for reimbursement
 . Residents pay for their own meals and their own travel to Bainbridge Isl
 and. There is no dedicated studio\; residents work in the house.\nDuration
 : Three weeks\; residents stay one at a time with no overlap\n\nMore: http
 s://bloedelreserve.slideroom.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&ut
 m_medium=referral#/login/program/88209
URL:https://bloedelreserve.slideroom.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral#/login/program/88209
LOCATION:Bainbridge Island\, Washington\, USA\, between Seattle and the Kit
 sap Peninsula\, reachable by ferry from Seattle or by car via the Kitsap P
 eninsula. Residents must be 21 or older. International applicants are elig
 ible but are funded differently from domestic ones (see amount).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:penn-college-gallery-exhibitions-2027-28@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T130538Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Gallery at Penn College: 2027-28 Call for Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:The Gallery at Penn College is accepting proposals for solo\, t
 wo-person and group exhibitions in its 2027-28 season. All entries are jur
 ied through a blind selection process by a gallery committee of faculty\, 
 staff\, K-12 art educators and community artists. The space is 3\,000 squa
 re feet with 82 to 250 running feet of linear wall depending on configurat
 ion and a ceiling height of 11 feet 4 inches\, and all exhibitions are ins
 talled by gallery staff. Site-specific installations requiring artist inst
 allation need an approved planning document first. Campus visits are a val
 ued part of programming though some exhibitions are scheduled without one\
 ; visiting artists give a 20 to 30 minute gallery talk at the public recep
 tion\, and are encouraged to propose class-specific programmes or communit
 y workshops. Promotional support includes an annual gallery catalogue\, po
 stcards\, press releases and web and social coverage. Applications require
  10 to 15 digital images (JPG only\, max 4 MB each)\, an image list with d
 imensions and medium\, a CV and an artist statement.\n\nOrganisation: The 
 Gallery at Penn College (Pennsylvania College of Technology)\nLocation: Wi
 lliamsport\, Pennsylvania\, USA\, on the Pennsylvania College of Technolog
 y campus. Travel note: Williamsport Regional Airport connects only to Wash
 ington Dulles\, with no other direct flights or trains\, so international 
 travel involves a connection. No nationality restriction is stated.\nAward
 : Housing\, meals\, a solo exhibition honorarium\, and a shipping and trav
 el stipend are all provided. Specific figures are not published in the cal
 l. No application fee is stated.\nDuration: Exhibition slot within the 202
 7-28 season\; review takes place during autumn semester with artists notif
 ied in January\n\nMore: https://www.pct.edu/gallery/exhibitions-entry-form
 ?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.pct.edu/gallery/exhibitions-entry-form?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Williamsport\, Pennsylvania\, USA\, on the Pennsylvania College of
  Technology campus. Travel note: Williamsport Regional Airport connects on
 ly to Washington Dulles\, with no other direct flights or trains\, so inte
 rnational travel involves a connection. No nationality restriction is stat
 ed.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
